	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right">07 September 2012 11:36</span>

	                    Community Commitment two years on


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p class="MsoNormal"></p>
<table summary="box">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>A community policing campaign, which celebrates its second
anniversary this month, continues to meet the needs of the public
in Edinburgh, the Lothians and the Scottish Borders.
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In September 2010 Lothian and Borders Police
launched its Community Commitment pledge across the Force area.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The key principle of the initiative is to
engage closely with local communities to identify the issues or
concerns that impact upon their areas and respond accordingly.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Through their sustained dialogue with
residents and businesses, officers continue to carry out a number
of initiatives aimed at improving the quality of life for
everyone.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In the Pentlands area of Edinburgh, local
officers launched Operation Cipher on Wednesday 24<sup>th</sup>
August this year.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Following robust community engagement and
information gathering police carried out a series of raids at
various addresses over a two-week period to remove those involved
in drug crime from the area.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Over &pound;80,000 worth of Heroin and around &pound;2,000
worth of cannabis were seized and five people were arrested and
charged with alleged drug offences.</p>
&nbsp;</td>
<td class="ImmTextAlign_Left ImmVerticalAlign_Top">
&nbsp;<img width="200" alt="Chief Constable David Strang" title="Chief Constable David Strang" src="/images/cc_strang.jpg" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 5px" height="300"/>
<table style="WIDTH: 214px; HEIGHT: 21px" summary="box">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class="ImmTextAlign_Center"><span class="legend">Chief
Constable David Strang</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p class="MsoNormal">Focus was also given to improving community
relations and tackling low-level offences such as antisocial
behaviour and youth related disturbances.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">To assist with this, police and their partner
agencies arranged a five-a-side football tournament for local
youths.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The tournament was a joint intervention event
between police, the Scottish Football Association and the No Knives
Better Lives Campaign to promote alternative life choices that stop
young people becoming involved in crime.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Despite poor weather, around 25 children and
their parents attended and enjoyed excellent engagement with the
police.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">To ensure the local communities are
continually updated with the progress of Operation Cipher, a blog
is currently running on the Force website and members of the public
are welcome to leave their comments or raise any further concerns,
which the local policing teams can then address.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Community Officers in Midlothian identified a
serious problem for local farmers in the Pentland Hills through
their regular engagement.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">During the lambing season, it had previously
been observed that a number of sheep and young lambs die as a
result of dog attacks or because of stress brought on by antisocial
behaviour in the area.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In 2011 a seasonal campaign was launched to
protect sheep and lambs during the lambing season.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Having proven successful, the initiative was
launched again in 2012 with the assistance of the Pentland Hill
Ranger Service.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Officers and Rangers carried out joint patrols
on the Pentland Hills to engage with dog walkers and other members
of the public to provide advice and guidance on appropriate control
measures for their pets.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Information on protecting the local wildlife
was also offered and anyone found to be involved in antisocial
behaviour was dealt with appropriately.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The campaign was well received by farmers and
public alike and reports of livestock attacks fell from around ten
in previous years, to none this year.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Increased visibility of police is at the core
of Community Commitment and in East Lothian, policing teams were
determined to improve their presence within rural areas.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In March, April and May of this year, police
teamed with the East Lothian Council Mobile Library Service as part
of a joint initiative.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoBodyText">Community Beat Officers boarded the mobile
book bus as it visited various country regions in the Haddington
sector to increase engagement and provide greater reassurance to
rural residents in East Lothian.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Through a number of channels, police provided
advanced notification as to when and where the bus would visit and
encouraged members of these communities to turn out and speak with
their local policing teams.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In each town and village, a good attendance by
residents was observed and a number of local issues were raised
with the officers who have since worked alongside the community to
appropriately address these.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Furthermore, the presence of police during
this unique venture has helped build on the existing relationship
between Lothian and Borders Police and rural residents.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The public in Boghall, West Lothian have also
benefited from Community Commitment activity since its launch in
2010.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Between late 2011 and early 2012, police
observed an increase in youth-related antisocial behaviour
complaints within the town, which included vandalism and
fire-raising.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">To address this issue, local officers and
other partner agencies launched a Week of Action aimed at improving
community pride and educating youths on the dangers of reckless and
criminal behaviour.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">During the week pupils from various year
groups at Boghall Primary were given a number of different
presentations to highlight the risks associated with substance
abuse; promote road safety and encourage tolerance and
understanding when dealing with minority groups.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Litter picks were also arranged at both St
Columbas and Boghall Primary school where over 50 bags of rubbish
were collected &ndash; improving the landscape of Boghall and helping to
instil a sense of community pride in the participating youths.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Information packs on cycle safety were then
distributed to many school children, while advice and guidance on
dog fouling and doorstep crime were issued throughout the
community.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">High-visibility foot and cycle patrols were
carried out throughout the week, offering reassurance to members of
the public and deterring further incidents from occurring.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">As a result of this activity Boghall has seen
a fall in low-level crime and anti-social behaviour as well a rise
in community confidence and engagement with local police and other
emergency services and local authorities.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Shortly after the Community Commitment launch
two years ago, officers in the Church Square area of Galashiels
were made aware of ongoing concerns relating to an increase in
crime and antisocial behaviour and a decline in the upkeep of the
area.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">To address these issues, a multi-agency task
team was put together featuring officers from Safer Communities,
Community Beat Officers, Antisocial Behaviour Team along with
representatives from Scottish Borders Housing Association (SBHA)
and local Community Wardens.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In February 2011 the group undertook a day of
action to engage with all residents and build a profile on the
nature and extent of the problems being experienced within the
area.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">High-visibility patrols were carried out to
deter crime and offer reassurance while Community Wardens and
officers searched for evidence of littering, vandalism and graffiti
and dealt with those found to be responsible.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Advice and guidance was provided to all local
residents on the various channels for reporting crime or making a
complaint, while officers gathered intelligence on those believed
to be responsible for the issues affecting Church Square.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Known offenders in the area were met with and
offered various intervention routes to stem any further incidents
occurring in the area.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">To increase the level of community pride, a
multi-agency project group was formed to carry out various local
initiatives aimed at improving the look of Church Square and
getting the community involved in caring for their
neighbourhood.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Among these initiatives was the removal of an
old flowerbed, which had been previously used as a dumping ground
for general waste.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">This was replaced by a new waste disposal site
containing appropriate receptacles for general waste as well as a
designated area for recycling.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Prior to its installation, only three bags per
fortnight were uplifted from Church Square for recycling. However,
this has continued to rise since 2011 and into 2012, with over 80
bags being collected in August this year.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The area saw a 26% reduction in antisocial
behaviour over the first six months of 2011 and a further 37%
reduction in the first six months of 2012.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong>Chief Constable David Strang</strong>
added: "Through our community commitment we have made significant
progress in tackling the issues that matter to the people and
businesses we police.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">"I am pleased to see that we continue to build
on the strong links we have with local communities and we will
continue to deliver on their priorities to ensure neighbourhoods
can flourish.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p>"Local policing is at the heart of everything w<span>e do, and I
am confident this will remain to be case as we move to become a
single service.</span></p>
